article.headline: Hornets stung by Wolves in final minute
article.linkText: Davis injured, Floyd ejected in Hornets' loss
article.story: MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Sam Cassell's case for a first invitation to the All-Star game keeps getting stronger. Cassell had 22 points, including seven in the final 2½ minutes, to lead the Minnesota Timberwolves to a 97-90 victory over the New Orleans Hornets on Monday. "I'm supposed to make wide-open shots. I'm supposed to make shots with guys hanging all over me," said Cassell, who made four jump shots in the fourth quarter. "That's why I have the ball in my hands down the stretch. Give my teammates credit. They have a lot to do with my success this year." Cassell, in his 11th NBA season, is averaging a career-high 20.9 points a game along with 7.3 assists. "He makes big shots," coach Flip Saunders said, pleased that Troy Hudson's return from an ankle injury allowed him to rest Cassell more before the final period. "He had the ability to be a little fresher." Kevin Garnett led the Timberwolves with 29 points, 15 rebounds and seven assists, drawing a foul with 18.2 seconds left that led to Hornets coach Tim Floyd's ejection. Baron Davis had 25 points for New Orleans before mildly spraining his left ankle midway through the fourth quarter with his team trailing 85-84. Missing their star, the Hornets lost their cool. "It hurts, but we still played well enough to where we should have won the game," Darrell Armstrong said. "There were just some calls that didn't go our way." Armstrong beat the shot clock with a 3-pointer that put the Hornets up 90-87 with 3:30 to go, but Cassell hit a 10-footer to cut the lead to one. After a missed dunk by Stacey Augmon, Cassell converted a jump shot from 18 feet on the other end to put the Timberwolves ahead 91-90 with 1:48 left. P.J. Brown was called for a double-dribble in the post, the first disputed call by New Orleans. Cassell drained a 17-footer from the wing to make it 93-90 with 1:02 remaining, and Steve Smith then missed a long jumper. Garnett got fouled as he awkwardly made a shot in the lane on the other end and Floyd went crazy, believing Garnett got away with at travel. He chucked his jacket off, kicked a bouncing ball into the seats, got ejected and angrily chased after referee Phil Robinson. Assistant Alvin Gentry took over for the final 18 seconds. "We didn't get a break at the end," Floyd said. "On the double-dribble, I thought it was clear the defender had touched the ball. And then I thought it was a travel." Minnesota made two more free throws after the ejection to seal its ninth straight home win. Latrell Sprewell added 15 points for the Wolves, who took over the Midwest Division lead from San Antonio last week and are 18-4 since Dec. 1. "We're not looking at the standings," Garnett said. "Our focus is on playing good basketball into the All-Star break." The Hornets, who had to put second-leading scorer David Wesley on the injured list with a sprained toe over the weekend, got another strong contribution from their bench. Robert Traylor, reaching double figures in scoring for the fourth time in six games, had 11 points and four rebounds, Augmon added 10 and Smith had nine. "We had opportunities to win the basketball game," Davis said. "We just need to suck it up and get ready for Wednesday." The Hornets host Philadelphia then, and Davis does not know whether he will be ready to play in the game. The Wolves got two players back from ankle injuries: Hudson and forward Gary Trent. Hudson missed the first 25 games this season with a severe sprain that he reaggravated Dec. 23 in his second game back -- causing him to miss 11 more. A valuable performer in the playoffs last season, Hudson looked even quicker than he was before he got hurt -- racing all over the court for six points in 15 minutes. Trent, who missed the last four games, was scoreless in seven minutes. ^Notes:@ Excluding the lockout-shortened 1998-99 season, this was the Wolves' ninth straight Martin Luther King Day home game. They are 8-1. ... Floyd is 0-8 lifetime against Minnesota.
